{"title_ko":"부드러운 반숙 달걀 (엄마 달걀)","title_en":"Soft-Boiled Eggs with Soy Dipping Sauce ('Mama Eggs')","source_language":"en","ingredients":[{"name_ko":"달걀","name_en":"Eggs","quantity":"원하는 만큼 / as many as needed","notes":"Size and freshness affect cook time; older eggs may need slightly longer"},{"name_ko":"간장","name_en":"Soy sauce","quantity":"눈대중으로 / to visual judgment","notes":"Poured until the ratio 'looks right' — a learned intuition, not a fixed measure"},{"name_ko":"참기름","name_en":"Sesame oil","quantity":"눈대중으로 / to visual judgment","notes":"Added to taste alongside soy sauce"},{"name_ko":"설탕","name_en":"Sugar","quantity":"약간 / a little","notes":"Just enough to balance the saltiness of the soy sauce"},{"name_ko":"파 (대파 또는 쪽파)","name_en":"Green onion (scallion)","quantity":"적당량 / to taste","notes":"Sliced very finely for garnish"}],"steps":[{"step_number":1,"instruction_ko":"냄비에 물을 넣고 완전히 끓을 때까지 가열합니다. 작은 기포가 아닌, 완전한 끓음이어야 합니다.","instruction_en":"Bring a pot of water to a full rolling boil — not just small bubbles, but a vigorous, full boil.","hidden_intent":"A full rolling boil ensures consistent heat from the moment the egg enters the water, which is critical for precise soft-boil timing. Starting in under-boiling water throws off the six-minute window."},{"step_number":2,"instruction_ko":"숟가락을 사용하여 달걀을 조심스럽게 끓는 물에 넣습니다.","instruction_en":"Using a spoon, gently lower the eggs into the boiling water one at a time.","hidden_intent":"Lowering eggs with a spoon prevents cracking from impact and protects the delicate membrane just inside the shell, which is especially important for soft-boiled eggs that will be peeled while still tender."},{"step_number":3,"instruction_ko":"부드러운 반숙은 정확히 6분, 완숙은 8분 동안 삶습니다. 단, 달걀의 크기와 신선도에 따라 시간이 조금 더 필요할 수 있습니다.","instruction_en":"Cook for exactly 6 minutes for soft-boiled, or 8 minutes for hard-boiled. However, adjust slightly based on the size and age of the egg — some eggs need a little more time.","hidden_intent":"The '6 minutes' is a baseline learned through repetition, not a universal rule. The cook is teaching attentiveness over rigidity — the ability to read the egg rather than blindly follow a timer is the real skill being transmitted."},{"step_number":4,"instruction_ko":"달걀이 익는 동안 소스를 만듭니다. 간장, 참기름, 설탕을 그릇에 넣고 '딱 맞아 보일 때까지' 조절하며 섞습니다.","instruction_en":"While the eggs cook, prepare the dipping sauce. Combine soy sauce, sesame oil, and a little sugar in a small bowl, adjusting each until the mixture looks and smells balanced.","hidden_intent":"The instruction 'pour until it looks right' encodes a deeply personal sensory calibration — the ratio is not fixed but is felt through years of repetition. The cook is describing 손맛 (son-mat): the intuitive, embodied knowledge that cannot be fully written down, only absorbed through practice and observation."},{"step_number":5,"instruction_ko":"달걀이 다 익으면 즉시 찬물에 담급니다. 이렇게 하면 잔열로 인한 추가 조리를 멈출 수 있습니다.","instruction_en":"As soon as the eggs are done, transfer them immediately to cold water. This stops the cooking process and prevents the yolk from overcooking.","hidden_intent":"The ice bath or cold water shock is a precision technique disguised as a simple step. For soft-boiled eggs, even 30 extra seconds of residual heat can push a jammy yolk toward fully set. Speed here is essential."},{"step_number":6,"instruction_ko":"달걀을 조심스럽게 껍질을 벗깁니다. 반숙 달걀은 흰자가 부드러워 쉽게 부서질 수 있으니 주의합니다.","instruction_en":"Peel the eggs carefully. Soft-boiled eggs are delicate — the whites are tender and can break easily if handled roughly.","hidden_intent":"Peeling a soft-boiled egg is a tactile skill. The cook is warning that force will ruin the result; patience and a light touch are required. This is another moment where embodied knowledge — learned by feel, not instruction — determines success."},{"step_number":7,"instruction_ko":"껍질을 벗긴 달걀에 소스를 끼얹고, 잘게 썬 파를 위에 올려 완성합니다.","instruction_en":"Spoon the dipping sauce over the peeled eggs and garnish with very finely sliced green onion.","hidden_intent":"The fine cut of the green onion is intentional — it should melt into the dish visually and texturally, providing freshness without overpowering the delicate egg. Coarse cuts would disrupt the softness of the overall dish."}],"loanwords_detected":[],"cultural_notes":"This recipe carries what Koreans call 손맛 (son-mat) — literally 'hand taste,' the untranslatable quality that a specific cook's touch imparts to food. The mother never measured because measurement was not how she learned; she learned through her hands, her eyes, and repetition across seasons. The instruction 'pour until it looks right' is not vagueness — it is the honest transmission of embodied knowledge that resists quantification.

The name 'mama eggs' (엄마 달걀) is itself a cultural artifact. Food names within families often carry more meaning than the recipe itself — they encode memory, love, and identity across generations. The fact that grandchildren now use the same name without being taught to do so illustrates how Korean culinary tradition is transmitted not through cookbooks but through shared meals, observation, and the emotional weight of a dish made by someone you love.

This recipe also reflects a broader Korean domestic cooking philosophy: precision is a starting point, not a destination. The six-minute rule is taught first, but the real lesson is learning when to deviate from it. Mastery is demonstrated not by following instructions perfectly, but by knowing when the instructions no longer apply."}
